ial support on the picket lines they've receivedfrom Eastern's pilots, the Machinists said Friday they'll continuestriking together in the face of what they call the company's``divide-and-conquer'' strategy.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Lawyers for Eastern Airlines Machinists said theywill mount a legal battle to get wages owed to striking unionmembers and repeated accusations that the crippled carrier timed itsbankruptcy filing to make sure workers went unpaid.   Machinists who expected to be paid Thursday instead had theirfinal pre-strike paychecks withheld by Eastern as part of itspetition for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of thefederal Bankruptcy Code.   Robert Clayman, a Washington-based attorney for the Machinists,said Friday he would file papers soon in U.S. Bankruptcy Court inManhattan to ``correct the pay situation ``and make sure theseemployees get paid as quickly as possible.''</TEXT><DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Anxious to protect itself from potentialasbestos liability claims arising out of a past business, RaytechCorp. filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 offederal bankruptcy laws.   Raytech, a multinational manufacturing holding company based inShelton, Conn., said Friday in a prepared statement that it wasforced to take its voluntary action in U.S. Bankruptcy Court inBridgeport, Conn., because ``all other potential avenues forresolution of the issue in the courts have proven to be ineffectiveor impossible.''   The bankruptcy action involves only the holding company and notany of its manufacturing subsidiaries. Raytech makes specialtyengineered products for industrial, auto, aerospace and militarycustomers.</TEXT><DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Raising taxes to solve the savings and loancrisis could save taxpayers $138 billion over the next 30 years, acongressman critical of federal regulators' handling of the crisissaid.   Congress and Americans were misinformed about the costs of savingthe troubled thrift industry, said U.S. Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, whoalso suggested Friday that top thrift regulators step aside after heheard that the deficit of the Federal Savings and Loan InsuranceCorp. had quadrupled from $14 billion in 1987 to at least $56billion in 1988.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two shareholders of BankAmerica Corp. have suedcompany officers over a student-loan fiasco that could cost a groupof banks $450 million to $650 million.   Greenfield andamp; Chimicles, a Haverford, Pa.-based law firm, saidFriday it was representing two shareholders in the suit, filed inthe Court of Chancery in Wilmington, Del.   BankAmerica announced Wednesday it was boosting its first-quarterreserves to cover its part in losses that resulted from an unusuallyhigh default rate on student vocational loans for which it acted astrustee.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The European Community Commission urged theUnited States to adopt the European production standard forhigh-definition television, saying the European approach would bebetter for consumers and the TV industry than a competing U.S.proposal.   The commission's Washington delegation sent a letter outliningits approach and criteria for a single worldwide HDTV productionstandard to the State and Commerce departments, it was disclosedFriday.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices fell in relatively quiet trading Friday as the DowJones average of 30 industrials dropped 9.29 to 2,282.14.   Goverment bond prices tumbled and interest rates surged.   The dollar finished higher against most major currencies.   Soybean futures prices finished lower after gyrating widely,grain futures finished mixed, silver futures gained while goldretreated, livestock and meat futures advanced and energy futureswere mixed.</TEXT></DOC>